    The root cause of the crash is a "Use-After-Free" error occurring within    
    the destroy_list function.                                                  
                                                                                
    Walkthrough of the program state:                                           
                                                                                
     1 Initialization: In main, a linked list is constructed: a -> b -> c.      
        • a (value 1) points to b.                                              
        • b (value 2) points to c.                                              
        • c (value 3) points to nullptr.                                        
     2 destroy_list(a): Called from main at line 21.                            
     3 The Loop (for loop at line 12):                                          
        • First iteration: cur points to a. delete cur (line 13) frees the      
          memory pointed to by a.                                               
        • Loop increment: The loop attempts to evaluate cur = cur->next.        
          Because cur (the node a) has already been deallocated in the          
          previous line, accessing cur->next is a Use-After-Free. The memory    
          where a->next was stored is no longer valid or accessible as a Node   
          object.                                                               
                                                                                
    The Defect:                                                                 
                                                                                
    The loop structure for (Node *cur = head; cur != nullptr; cur = cur->next)  
    attempts to access the next pointer of the current node after the current   
    node has already been deleted.                                              
                                                                                
    Fixes:                                                                      
                                                                                
    Minimal Local Fix:                                                          
                                                                                
    To fix this, you must store the address of the next node before deleting    
    the current node, so that you can continue the loop safely.                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
     static void destroy_list(Node *head) {                                     
         Node *cur = head;                                                      
         while (cur != nullptr) {                                               
             Node *next_node = cur->next; // Store next before deleting         
             delete cur;                                                        
             cur = next_node; // Move to the stored next node                   
         }                                                                      
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Root-Cause Fix:                                                             
                                                                                
    The root cause is a pattern that is inherently unsafe for manual memory     
    management. Using raw pointers and manual delete calls is error-prone. The  
    better, more robust approach is to:                                         
                                                                                
     1 Use Modern C++ containers: Use std::unique_ptr for node ownership or     
       std::list / std::forward_list from the standard library to manage        
       memory automatically. If you use std::unique_ptr<Node>, you would not    
       need to manually delete nodes in a loop, as the destructor would handle  
       the cleanup recursively.                                                 
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    I have identified the root cause of the crash. To resolve it, apply the     
    "minimal local fix" provided above: cache the next pointer before calling   
    delete on the current node. For long-term maintainability, consider         
    refactoring the code to use smart pointers (std::unique_ptr) to avoid       
    manual memory management errors entirely.                                   
                                                                                
